performance_optimizations.description:
Current parallel scan uses strided thread assignment (thread t processes every num_threads-th qualifying block), which causes random seeks on HDD when blocks are scattered. HDD has ~10ms seek latency, so 64 threads accessing non-contiguous blocks creates disk thrashing.

Specific changes to q3.cpp:

1. After identifying qualifying_blocks (line 172), SORT them to ensure sequential file order:
   std::sort(qualifying_blocks.begin(), qualifying_blocks.end());

2. Replace strided thread assignment (lines 186-198) with atomic work queue for dynamic load balancing:
   std::atomic<size_t> next_block_idx{0};
   for (size_t t = 0; t < num_threads; ++t) {
       order_threads.emplace_back([&]() {
           auto& local_map = local_qualified_orders[t];
           local_map.reserve(estimated_qualified_orders / num_threads + 1000);

           while (true) {
               size_t idx = next_block_idx.fetch_add(1, std::memory_order_relaxed);
               if (idx >= qualifying_blocks.size()) break;

               size_t block_id = qualifying_blocks[idx];
               size_t start_row = block_id * block_size;
               size_t end_row = std::min(start_row + block_size, orders_row_count);

               for (size_t i = start_row; i < end_row; ++i) {
                   if (o_orderdate[i] < date_1995_03_15 && building_custkeys.count(o_custkey[i]) > 0) {
                       local_map[o_orderkey[i]] = {o_orderdate[i], o_shippriority[i]};
                   }
               }
           }
       });
   }

3. Apply same pattern to lineitem scan (lines 258-288): sort lineitem_qualifying_blocks and use atomic work queue.

Benefits: Sequential block processing reduces HDD seeks from ~30-50 seeks/sec (random strided access) to ~5-10 seeks/sec (mostly sequential). Dynamic work queue eliminates thread idle time from imbalanced block sizes. On HDD with 100MB/s sequential vs ~10MB/s random I/O, this can provide 3-5x I/O speedup.

Expected improvement: Orders scan I/O component: ~400ms (I/O-bound portion) → ~150-200ms (better sequential access). Lineitem I/O similarly improves. Reference: storage/persistent-storage.md recommends sequential access patterns for HDD.

Current code mmaps all 4 orders columns (orderkey, custkey, orderdate, shippriority) with default lazy page-in. The date column (o_orderdate) is accessed first for filtering, causing page faults during scan. Using MAP_POPULATE flag during mmap for date columns pre-faults pages during mmap call, parallelizing I/O with subsequent computation.

Specific changes to q3.cpp:

1. Modify mmapFile helper (lines 21-45) to accept optional flags parameter:
   const void* mmapFile(const std::string& path, size_t& size_out, int mmap_flags = MAP_PRIVATE) {
       // ... existing code ...
       void* ptr = mmap(nullptr, size_out, PROT_READ, mmap_flags, fd, 0);
       // ... rest unchanged ...
   }

2. For date columns, use MAP_POPULATE:
   Line 150: const int32_t* o_orderdate = (const int32_t*)mmapFile(gendb_dir + "/orders/o_orderdate.bin", orders_orderdate_size, MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_POPULATE);
   Line 226: const int32_t* l_shipdate = (const int32_t*)mmapFile(gendb_dir + "/lineitem/l_shipdate.bin", lineitem_shipdate_size, MAP_PRIVATE | MAP_POPULATE);

3. Keep other columns with default lazy paging to avoid over-committing memory.

Benefits: MAP_POPULATE pre-faults pages during mmap, causing kernel to read data ahead. For date columns (~60MB for orders, ~240MB for lineitem), this takes ~600ms + 2400ms = 3000ms on HDD at 100MB/s sequential, BUT it happens in parallel with other work (customer scan, other column mmaps). Reduces page fault stalls during scan by 30-50%.

Caution: MAP_POPULATE blocks the mmap call until data is paged in. Only use for columns accessed immediately. Total memory footprint increases (~300MB).

Expected improvement: Reduced page fault overhead during scans: ~40-80ms saved (10-15% of I/O stall time). Reference: storage/persistent-storage.md lists MAP_POPULATE for hot columns.

Current code does NOT use a Bloom filter (removed after iter 1 analysis showed mixed benefits). However, for the lineitem probe phase, a properly-sized Bloom filter can skip ~93-95% of non-matching lineitem rows (~56M of 60M) before expensive hash table probes.

Specific changes to q3.cpp:

1. Add Bloom filter header at top:
   #include <vector>
   // Simple Bloom filter using std::vector<uint64_t> as bit array
   class BloomFilter {
       std::vector<uint64_t> bits;
       size_t num_bits;
       size_t num_hashes;
   public:
       BloomFilter(size_t n, double fpr = 0.01) {
           num_bits = -n * std::log(fpr) / (std::log(2) * std::log(2));
           num_hashes = (num_bits / n) * std::log(2);
           bits.resize((num_bits + 63) / 64, 0);
       }
       void insert(int32_t key) {
           uint64_t h = std::hash<int32_t>{}(key);
           for (size_t i = 0; i < num_hashes; ++i) {
               size_t pos = (h + i * (h >> 32)) % num_bits;
               bits[pos / 64] |= (1ULL << (pos % 64));
           }
       }
       bool contains(int32_t key) const {
           uint64_t h = std::hash<int32_t>{}(key);
           for (size_t i = 0; i < num_hashes; ++i) {
               size_t pos = (h + i * (h >> 32)) % num_bits;
               if (!(bits[pos / 64] & (1ULL << (pos % 64)))) return false;
           }
           return true;
       }
   };

2. After merging qualified_orders (line 213), build Bloom filter in parallel:
   auto t_bloom_start = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();
   BloomFilter order_bloom(qualified_orders.size(), 0.01); // 1% FPR

   // Parallel Bloom build
   std::vector<int32_t> order_keys;
   order_keys.reserve(qualified_orders.size());
   for (const auto& entry : qualified_orders) {
       order_keys.push_back(entry.first);
   }

   const size_t chunk_size = (order_keys.size() + num_threads - 1) / num_threads;
   std::vector<std::thread> bloom_threads;
   for (size_t t = 0; t < num_threads; ++t) {
       bloom_threads.emplace_back([&, t]() {
           size_t start = t * chunk_size;
           size_t end = std::min(start + chunk_size, order_keys.size());
           for (size_t i = start; i < end; ++i) {
               order_bloom.insert(order_keys[i]);
           }
       });
   }
   for (auto& th : bloom_threads) th.join();

3. In lineitem scan loop (line 266), add Bloom pre-check:
   if (l_shipdate[i] <= date_1995_03_15) continue;
   if (!order_bloom.contains(l_orderkey[i])) continue; // Bloom filter
   auto it = qualified_orders.find(l_orderkey[i]);
   // ... rest unchanged ...

Benefits: Bloom filter with 1% FPR skips ~94-95% of non-matching lineitem rows (~56M out of 60M) before hash table probe. Bloom lookup: ~5-10ns vs hash table probe: ~15-30ns (with Abseil). For 56M saved probes, this saves ~280-1120ms. Build cost: ~20-40ms parallel.

Expected improvement: Join/aggregation: 124ms → 80-100ms (-24-44ms from reduced probes). Build cost: +20-40ms. Net: -4-24ms. Combined with faster hash tables (priority 1), net savings increase. Reference: indexing/bloom-filters.md recommends for low join selectivity.

Both orders scan (o_orderdate < date_1995_03_15) and lineitem scan (l_shipdate > date_1995_03_15) perform sequential scalar date comparisons. These are vectorizable using AVX2 (process 8 int32 comparisons per instruction) or AVX-512 (16 comparisons).

Specific changes to q3.cpp:

1. Add SIMD header: #include <immintrin.h>

2. In orders scan loop (lines 192-196), vectorize date filtering:
   for (size_t i = start_row; i < end_row; ) {
       // SIMD batch processing
       const __m256i threshold = _mm256_set1_epi32(date_1995_03_15);
       size_t simd_end = (end_row - i) >= 8 ? end_row - ((end_row - i) % 8) : i;

       for (; i < simd_end; i += 8) {
           __m256i dates = _mm256_loadu_si256((__m256i*)&o_orderdate[i]);
           __m256i cmp = _mm256_cmpgt_epi32(threshold, dates); // dates < threshold
           int mask = _mm256_movemask_ps(_mm256_castsi256_ps(cmp));

           if (mask == 0) continue; // All 8 rows filtered out

           // Process matching lanes
           for (int lane = 0; lane < 8; ++lane) {
               if (mask & (1 << lane)) {
                   if (building_custkeys.count(o_custkey[i + lane]) > 0) {
                       local_map[o_orderkey[i + lane]] = {o_orderdate[i + lane], o_shippriority[i + lane]};
                   }
               }
           }
       }

       // Scalar tail
       for (; i < end_row; ++i) {
           if (o_orderdate[i] < date_1995_03_15 && building_custkeys.count(o_custkey[i]) > 0) {
               local_map[o_orderkey[i]] = {o_orderdate[i], o_shippriority[i]};
           }
       }
   }

3. Apply same pattern to lineitem scan (lines 264-274) for l_shipdate > date_1995_03_15.

Benefits: AVX2 processes 8 comparisons per instruction. For ~7.35M orders rows scanned (across all threads), this reduces comparison count from 7.35M to ~920K vector ops. For ~32M lineitem rows scanned (after zone map skipping), reduces from 32M to ~4M vector ops. Date filtering is ~10-15% of scan CPU time, SIMD reduces by 6-8x → saves 8-13% of CPU time.

Challenges: Branching on mask bits adds overhead. For dense matches (high selectivity), scalar may be competitive. For sparse matches, gather/scatter overhead dominates.

Expected improvement: Orders scan CPU: ~15-25ms saved. Join/aggregation CPU: ~10-15ms saved. Total: ~25-40ms. Reference: parallelism/simd.md.

Current orders scan evaluates two predicates: (1) o_orderdate < date_1995_03_15 (49% selectivity), (2) building_custkeys.count(o_custkey[i]) (20% selectivity after customer filter). The code evaluates date first (line 193), then hash lookup. For optimal short-circuiting, evaluate the most selective (cheapest to fail) predicate first.

Analysis: Date comparison is ~1-2ns (simple int32 compare). Hash lookup is ~15-30ns (with std, ~10-15ns with Abseil). Date selectivity: 49% pass. Custkey selectivity: 20% pass. Combined selectivity: ~10% pass.

Current: 100% pay date cost (1-2ns), 49% pay hash cost (15-30ns). Average: 1-2ns + 0.49 × 15-30ns = 8.5-16.7ns per row.
Optimized (hash first): 100% pay hash cost (15-30ns), 20% pay date cost (1-2ns). Average: 15-30ns + 0.2 × 1-2ns = 15.2-30.4ns per row.

Conclusion: CURRENT ORDER IS CORRECT. Date filter is cheaper and more selective as a first-pass filter. However, we can optimize by caching the hash table size check.

Alternative optimization: Materialize building_custkeys as a sorted array or bit-vector (since custkey is dense integer space 1-1.5M), then use binary search or bit-check (O(1)) instead of hash lookup.

Actually, a better approach: Since customer c_custkey is in range [1, 1500000] and 20% are BUILDING segment, use a bitvector (188KB for 1.5M bits) instead of hash set:

1. Replace line 131: std::unordered_set<int32_t> building_custkeys → std::vector<uint8_t> building_custkeys_bitmap((customer_row_count + 7) / 8, 0);

2. Replace lines 134-137:
   for (size_t i = 0; i < customer_row_count; ++i) {
       if (c_mktsegment[i] == 0) {
           int32_t custkey = c_custkey[i];
           building_custkeys_bitmap[custkey / 8] |= (1 << (custkey % 8));
       }
   }

3. Replace line 193 lookup:
   int32_t custkey = o_custkey[i];
   if (o_orderdate[i] < date_1995_03_15 && (building_custkeys_bitmap[custkey / 8] & (1 << (custkey % 8)))) {
       local_map[o_orderkey[i]] = {o_orderdate[i], o_shippriority[i]};
   }

Benefits: Bit-vector lookup is ~1-2ns (single memory load + bit test) vs hash lookup ~15-30ns (std) or ~10-15ns (Abseil). For 7.35M lookups, saves ~70-210ms.

Expected improvement: Orders scan: 506.6ms → 370-440ms (-65-135ms). This is a MAJOR optimization.
